Typing Pattern Analysis

↑ Back to top

Understanding Negative Values in Typing Data

Our analysis reveals that negative timing values are a normal and expected part of natural typing behavior, not data quality issues:

What Negative Values Mean:

  • Negative IL (Inter-key Latency): The next key is pressed before the previous key is released. This is extremely common in fast typing and represents overlapping keystrokes.
  • Negative RL (Release Latency): Keys are released in a different order than they were pressed. This happens when users quickly type combinations of keys.

Key Findings:

  • 86.8% of negative IL values are from regular typing (not modifier keys)
  • 100.0% of negative RL values coincide with negative IL values, indicating they represent the same fast-typing phenomenon
  • Common patterns include letter combinations that are typical of rapid typing sequences
  • These patterns are consistent across users and represent individual typing styles and speeds

Implications for Analysis:

Negative values should not be filtered out as errors. They contain valuable information about typing dynamics and are essential for accurate user authentication and typing pattern analysis. The high percentage of "unexpected" negative values (86.8%) actually represents normal fast typing behavior rather than data quality issues.

import pandas as pd

    analysis_results = json.load(f)
